    com.andreamazzon.session5.abstractclasses.basicexample
    This package illustrates a first basic example of abstract classes.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.abstractclasses.shapes
    Here you can see an example of why abstract classes can be useful: look at com.andreamazzon.session4.polymorphism.shapes.Shape Here we had to give a dummy implementation to the method computeArea(), which is overridden in the derived classes Circle, Triangle and Square.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.abstractclasses.simulators
    The classes in this package give a more complex example of inheritance in combination with composition: an abstract class StochasticProcessSimulator is defined, whose aim is the simulation of a general stochastic process.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.abstractclasses.usingsimulators
    The code in this package gives an example of a combination of inheritance and composition.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.anotherpackage
    In this package we illustrate the meaning of an interface with package access: we have a tester class, with a main method that is able to create an object of the public class ImplementingClass, which implements the interface PackageAccessInterface, both in the package com.andreamazzon.session5.packageaccessinterfaces.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.enumtype.currencies
    The code in this package shows an example of the enum type: it is useful when you have to group together and use a set of constant values (enumerated types, typically strings).
    com.andreamazzon.session5.explicitupcasting.goalkeepers
    The code in this package is meant to give a further insight on the upcasting of an object of an inherited class giving it a reference to an object of the base class.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.inheritinginterfaces
    Scope of this package is to illustrate that, differently from what happens with classes, multiple inheritance is possible for interfaces: an interface can indeed inherit from more than one interfaces.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.interfaceexample
    In this package we illustrate a first example of interface: and interface is a "completely abstract" class, as it only gives the returning type, name and arguments lists of the methods that a class "implementing" that interface must implement, and possibly static fields: it provides the "form" of a class implementing that interface, but not the implementation.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.interfacesandpolymorphism.band
    In this package we show another example of polymorphism, connected with interfaces.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.multipleinterfaceimplementation.animals
    Here we show how multiple implementation is possible with interfaces: the class Duck implements both the interfaces AnimalThatFlies (that has a method fly()) and AnimalThatSwims (that has a method swim()).
    com.andreamazzon.session5.nameclasheswithinterfaces
    This package illustrates possible problems due to name clashes when a class implements two interfaces which have two methods with the same name, same argument list but different return types.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.nomultipleinheritance
    In this package we show why multiple inheritance is not allowed in Java: if a class inherits from two base classes, it can happen that the two classes have a method with same name, same argument list and different implementation.
    com.andreamazzon.session5.packageaccessinterfaces
    In this package we illustrate the meaning of an interface with package access: we have an interface PackageAccessInterface, which has only package access.
    com.andreamazzon.session6.exceptions.commonexception
    In this package we see how a common run time error is handled in Java by an exception.
    com.andreamazzon.session6.exceptions.divisions
    The class Divider has a static void Divide method which serves as an example of how exceptions are handled and thrown.
    com.andreamazzon.session6.generics.containers
    The code in this package illustrates some features and uses of “Java Generics”, a term related to the definition and use of generic classes, interfaces and methods.
    com.andreamazzon.session6.generics.fibonacci
    The code in this package, together with the one in com.andeamazzon.session6.generics.readstring, shows an example of the use of generics.
